snippet.textDisplay: I learned in Medical Assisting classes that pens have those little holes so that is a child swallows a pen and it is lodged in their throat, air can still pass through. A doctor will insert a tool called a balloon catheter into the hole, once it is in, the catheter is filled with air and the end will balloon out, so it no longer can come back out of the hole. The doctor can then use this to pull the pen out of the esophagus.
snippet.textOriginal: I learned in Medical Assisting classes that pens have those little holes so that is a child swallows a pen and it is lodged in their throat, air can still pass through.
